WEBVTT

00:04.372 --> 00:06.140
(SPITS)

00:09.277 --> 00:10.478
(SPITS)

00:27.228 --> 00:28.296
(WHISPERS) Okay.

00:29.697 --> 00:31.332
Morning, roomie.

00:32.032 --> 00:33.434
Morning, roomie.

00:33.501 --> 00:35.769
I'm going to the market later.
You need more apples?

00:35.836 --> 00:38.672
No, but we need
more toilet paper.

00:39.240 --> 00:40.308
No prob.

00:42.476 --> 00:43.644
May I?

00:45.146 --> 00:46.647
No prob.

00:46.714 --> 00:47.981
(CHUCKLES)

00:48.048 --> 00:50.551
Angel Fluff Plus, two-ply,

00:50.618 --> 00:52.920
unscented, ultra-wide,
extra soft.

00:52.986 --> 00:55.523
Two-ply.
No prob.

00:58.626 --> 01:00.428
You have to hang
the toilet paper

01:00.494 --> 01:02.496
on the dispenser
the correct way.

01:02.563 --> 01:04.732
The paper goes over
on the top,

01:04.798 --> 01:07.501
not under hanging
against the wall.

01:07.568 --> 01:09.137
Sorry, I forgot
you like it like that.

01:09.203 --> 01:11.739
I don't "like it
like that."

01:11.805 --> 01:13.874
It's "right" like that.

01:14.208 --> 01:15.276
NBD.

01:16.810 --> 01:18.146
It's no big deal.

01:18.212 --> 01:19.713
I got to run.

01:21.649 --> 01:23.384
(DOOR OPENS, CLOSES)

01:24.752 --> 01:29.190
(UP-TEMPO VIOLIN
MUSIC PLAYING)

01:29.257 --> 01:30.391
Ms. Kohl?

01:30.458 --> 01:32.293
Hi, I'm Dr. Melendez.

01:32.360 --> 01:34.695
Sorry. I have to practice
whenever I can.

01:34.762 --> 01:37.165
I practice
whenever I can, too.

01:37.231 --> 01:38.999
We heard you
hurt your finger.

01:39.066 --> 01:40.201
Can we take a look?

01:40.268 --> 01:42.970
I got a crappy manicure
a couple days ago,

01:43.036 --> 01:45.473
and now my nail
looks disgusting.

01:45.539 --> 01:47.841
Paronychia.
It's an abscess caused by

01:47.908 --> 01:49.243
a common bacterial infection.

01:49.310 --> 01:51.212
We'll drain it, pack it,
and send you home.

01:51.279 --> 01:53.314
In 72 hours, the pain and
swelling will be much better,

01:53.381 --> 01:55.416
and you'll be back
to Paganini.

02:00.321 --> 02:01.822
Apologize already.

02:01.889 --> 02:04.525
(CHUCKLES) I did
nothing wrong.
So?

02:04.592 --> 02:05.826
You don't want
to be iced out

02:05.893 --> 02:08.362
by the future
Chief of Surgery forever.

02:08.429 --> 02:10.898
Lim could be Chief, too.
Andrews hasn't decided yet.

02:10.964 --> 02:12.700
Hey, Brown, Park.
Hustle in.

02:12.766 --> 02:14.435
EMTs are less than
a minute out.

02:14.502 --> 02:16.069
Park, make sure Bay 3's
good to go.

02:16.136 --> 02:17.538
EMT:
13-year-old female.

02:17.605 --> 02:19.707
Progressively worsening
epistaxis.

02:19.773 --> 02:22.610
Bolus on the bus.
BP 86/51.

02:22.676 --> 02:24.812
It won't stop!
I can't get it to stop!

02:24.878 --> 02:26.814
I got home,
and she was calling 911.

02:26.880 --> 02:27.981
Not your first nosebleed,
huh, Dad?

02:28.048 --> 02:29.683
Well, these things usually
go away on their own,

02:29.750 --> 02:31.852
but Riley claims she's been
like this for over an hour.

02:31.919 --> 02:34.855
Ugh! It's not a claim,
it's a fact!

02:34.922 --> 02:36.690
Gonna need to get her on
a monitor right away

02:36.757 --> 02:38.826
and apply 4%
phenylephrine solution.

02:38.892 --> 02:40.728
Gonna need to cauterize
the bleed.

02:40.794 --> 02:43.163
It's not my first
nosebleed either.

02:43.231 --> 02:47.100
**

02:47.167 --> 02:50.438
I have my premiere at Davies
this weekend,

02:50.504 --> 02:52.105
hence the manicure.

02:52.172 --> 02:55.643
Rosin, beeswax, that stuff
is tough to get off.

02:55.709 --> 02:57.077
You play?

02:57.144 --> 02:59.613
I know my way
around bow strings.

02:59.680 --> 03:02.450
I dabbled in archery
when I was in high school.

03:02.516 --> 03:05.085
I started when I was 5.

03:05.152 --> 03:07.855
I used to hum melodies
doing my homework,

03:07.921 --> 03:09.723
eating dinner,
taking out the trash.

03:09.790 --> 03:11.959
I wanted to be
a train conductor.

03:12.025 --> 03:13.527
Mm, there's still time.

03:15.929 --> 03:17.865
(INHALES SHARPLY)

03:17.931 --> 03:19.800
Ow.
She's numbed up.

03:19.867 --> 03:22.936
She shouldn't have
any pain in her finger.

03:23.003 --> 03:24.338
It's not my finger.

03:24.405 --> 03:26.507
It's further up,
by my knuckle.

03:26.574 --> 03:28.409
(THERMOMETER BEEPING)
No fever.

03:28.476 --> 03:29.777
Any body aches?

03:29.843 --> 03:31.812
Uh, a little.

03:31.879 --> 03:34.315
Playing violin all day
stresses out my neck
and shoulders.

03:34.382 --> 03:37.318
It's likely tendonitis
or mild arthritic pain.

03:37.385 --> 03:39.420
Or it might be
flesh-eating bacteria

03:39.487 --> 03:41.322
and we have may have to
cut off your finger.

03:43.724 --> 03:45.726
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

03:54.034 --> 03:55.269
There's the bleeder,

03:55.336 --> 03:57.505
at the posterior rim of
Kiesselbach's plexus.

03:59.206 --> 04:00.474
You called 911?

04:00.541 --> 04:01.975
She did.

04:03.711 --> 04:04.712
How you feeling, baby?

04:04.778 --> 04:05.913
Peachy.

04:05.979 --> 04:07.548
It's a nosebleed.
I'm handling it.

04:07.615 --> 04:08.949
She's my kid, too, Bruce.

04:09.016 --> 04:11.251
Bet you couldn't tell
they're divorced.

04:11.319 --> 04:12.953
DR. PARK: Well, why don't
I take Riley's parents

04:13.020 --> 04:14.087
to the waiting room
so we can...

04:14.154 --> 04:15.188
Talk about me.

04:15.255 --> 04:16.524
Adios.

04:22.029 --> 04:24.632
We need to know.

04:24.698 --> 04:27.835
Shaun, what do we need to do
to know for sure?

04:27.901 --> 04:30.871
We need to cut deeper
and get a swab.

04:30.938 --> 04:33.040
Fingers have thousands
of nerve endings.

04:33.106 --> 04:36.477
Clipping off even the tiniest
portion of Jas' finger

04:36.544 --> 04:38.846
could cause permanent damage
and be career-ending.

04:38.912 --> 04:41.882
But if it is
necrotizing fasciitis

04:41.949 --> 04:44.885
and we do nothing,
she could die.

04:44.952 --> 04:47.120
That would also
end her career.

04:48.188 --> 04:49.222
True.

04:49.289 --> 04:51.559
But the numbers, Shaun,
the data.

04:51.625 --> 04:53.927
There's almost no chance
that it's nec fasc.

04:53.994 --> 04:55.663
On the other hand,
if we test for it,

04:55.729 --> 04:57.197
we will definitely
do damage.

04:59.933 --> 05:01.602
Anything else?

05:04.405 --> 05:07.808
Do you hang your toilet paper
going over or under?

05:10.110 --> 05:11.579
Doesn't matter.

05:13.847 --> 05:16.216
STELLA: Before the nosebleeds,
it was tummy aches,

05:16.283 --> 05:17.851
insomnia, breathing pain.

05:17.918 --> 05:20.220
Every time, we'd rush her
to the pediatrician,

05:20.287 --> 05:22.022
but they couldn't
find anything,

05:22.089 --> 05:23.857
so we stopped taking her.

05:23.924 --> 05:25.693
You think she's faking it?

05:25.759 --> 05:28.429
A therapist said it was
likely her subconscious way

05:28.496 --> 05:30.431
of trying to get her family
back together.

05:30.498 --> 05:32.700
Well, divorce isn't easy
for adults.

05:32.766 --> 05:35.035
Why should kids be able
to deal with it any better?

05:35.102 --> 05:36.737
She disengaged,

05:36.804 --> 05:40.240
not just from us,
but her friends, school.

05:41.308 --> 05:42.910
It's been five years.

05:42.976 --> 05:45.679
She should have found
her new normal by now.

05:47.047 --> 05:48.582
(SIGHS)

05:50.150 --> 05:51.452
Looks like someone's
doing better.

05:51.519 --> 05:53.421
Nosebleed stopped,

05:53.487 --> 05:55.389
but Riley's nasal membranes
are pretty thin.

05:55.456 --> 05:58.892
You should be on the lookout
for future bleeds.

05:58.959 --> 06:03.397
Riley, have you been sniffing
or snorting any drugs lately?

06:03.464 --> 06:05.533
What? No way.
I wouldn't do that.

06:05.599 --> 06:07.635
There's a lot of stuff
out there that looks harmless,

06:07.701 --> 06:09.002
but...
She said no.

06:12.072 --> 06:13.507
Does FLONASE count?

06:15.543 --> 06:16.577
I was coughing.

06:16.644 --> 06:19.079
I had a stuffy nose,
itchy throat.

06:19.146 --> 06:20.448
I looked up my symptoms,

06:20.514 --> 06:23.016
because what the hell else
was I supposed to do?

06:23.083 --> 06:24.918
Vasomotor rhinitis fit.

06:24.985 --> 06:27.821
So I went to the drug store,
and I got some FLONASE.

06:27.888 --> 06:30.991
Misuse of steroid sprays
can thin out nasal membranes,

06:31.058 --> 06:32.392
causing terrible nosebleeds.

06:32.460 --> 06:35.095
Quit the FLONASE,
you're good to go.

06:35.162 --> 06:36.730
BRUCE: Thank you.

06:38.165 --> 06:40.167
Uh, I need you
to take her tonight.

06:40.233 --> 06:43.003
I had to skip a pitch to
an important V.C. to get here.

06:43.070 --> 06:44.605
Sorry, didn't mean
to take you away

06:44.672 --> 06:45.973
from anything important.

06:46.039 --> 06:47.975
You're provoking her.
You know she's an anxious kid.

06:48.041 --> 06:49.610
I'm not anxious, I'm sick.

06:49.677 --> 06:51.011
STELLA: Could you for once
have my back?

06:51.078 --> 06:52.513
BRUCE: What?
STELLA: This is your fault.

06:52.580 --> 06:54.281
She's playing us
against each other.

06:54.347 --> 06:55.583
(BREATHING RAGGEDLY)

06:55.649 --> 06:56.784
What's wrong?

06:56.850 --> 06:58.351
My breathing, it... it hurts.

06:58.418 --> 06:59.487
STELLA: Just relax, sweetie.

06:59.553 --> 07:00.888
Just stop, both of you.

07:00.954 --> 07:03.090
(COUGHING)

07:07.127 --> 07:09.963
Vasomotor rhinitis.

07:10.030 --> 07:13.000
That is a pretty unique
diagnosis for an 8th grader.

07:13.066 --> 07:14.668
You'll be numb in a minute.

07:14.735 --> 07:16.169
Seventh.

07:16.236 --> 07:17.838
And I was wrong.

07:17.905 --> 07:19.840
Doesn't matter.

07:19.907 --> 07:21.975
I get what
you're going through.

07:22.042 --> 07:24.211
You were smart, popular.

07:24.277 --> 07:25.979
We don't have anything
in common.

07:26.046 --> 07:27.781
I was never popular.

07:29.850 --> 07:32.352
I wore hand-me-downs
from Goodwill.

07:32.419 --> 07:34.187
I never knew my dad.

07:34.254 --> 07:37.691
My mom was sick.
I couldn't rely on her.

07:37.758 --> 07:40.060
You know, kids at
that age can be total...

07:40.127 --> 07:41.194
Jerks.

07:41.261 --> 07:43.330
Asshats. Turds.

07:43.396 --> 07:46.767
I wouldn't send
my worst enemy
back to junior high.

07:52.439 --> 07:55.042
I got so many D's
on my report card last year,

07:55.108 --> 07:56.476
I got held back.

07:58.178 --> 08:00.480
Now everyone treats me
like I'm stupid.

08:01.949 --> 08:03.751
It's humiliating.
(INHALES SHARPLY)

08:03.817 --> 08:05.819
How'd you deal with it?

08:08.088 --> 08:10.223
I said screw it.

08:10.290 --> 08:12.392
They already think I'm bad.

08:12.459 --> 08:15.663
I mess around in class,
leave campus,

08:15.729 --> 08:17.598
do whatever the hell I want.

08:19.266 --> 08:22.369
But you're still angry.

08:28.609 --> 08:31.378
I didn't let my past
define me

08:34.782 --> 08:38.686
and yours doesn't
have to define you.

08:39.853 --> 08:42.389
Repeating a grade
doesn't make you...

08:45.392 --> 08:46.459
What?

08:46.526 --> 08:47.695
What's wrong?

08:47.761 --> 08:49.262
Nothing.

08:49.329 --> 08:51.398
There doesn't seem to be
any active bleeding.

08:51.464 --> 08:54.401
But I coughed up blood.
That was real.

08:54.467 --> 08:56.937
It's possible it's just
post-nasal aspiration

08:57.004 --> 08:59.807
that the blood you
coughed up was from
the initial nosebleed,

08:59.873 --> 09:02.876
and it went down your throat,
into your lungs.

09:04.945 --> 09:07.815
But my chest,
it really hurts.

09:08.348 --> 09:10.450
**

09:10.517 --> 09:11.985
LEA: Hey, Shaun.
What's up?

09:12.052 --> 09:13.887
You forgot to put
your coffee cup

09:13.954 --> 09:15.923
in the dishwasher
before you left.

09:15.989 --> 09:17.658
Sorry, I was in a rush.

09:17.725 --> 09:19.359
And remember,
rinse it out

09:19.426 --> 09:21.194
before you put it
in the dishwasher.

09:21.261 --> 09:23.631
Noted.
And on the top rack.

09:23.697 --> 09:25.498
I got to go.
Me too.

09:25.565 --> 09:29.770
Morgan doesn't want to know
what's wrong with our patient.

09:29.837 --> 09:31.004
I find that hard to believe.

09:31.071 --> 09:33.506
They talk about bow strings.

09:33.573 --> 09:35.743
I don't know anything
about bow strings.

09:35.809 --> 09:39.046
They should be talking about
what's wrong with her.

09:39.112 --> 09:41.381
You can't always know, Shaun.

09:41.448 --> 09:43.516
Sometimes tests
aren't worth it.

09:43.583 --> 09:45.719
Sometimes we don't
have the right tests.

09:52.926 --> 09:54.962
(DOOR OPENS)

09:55.028 --> 09:57.330
**

09:57.397 --> 09:58.766
CLAIRE: What are
you doing in here?

09:58.832 --> 10:02.235
Lea and I disagree
about toilet paper.

10:02.302 --> 10:05.939
And you made a good point
about finding the right test.

10:06.606 --> 10:07.607
Thanks?

10:09.576 --> 10:11.411
I just did a test.

10:12.312 --> 10:13.580
On the toilet paper?

10:13.647 --> 10:16.116
Every toilet paper roll
in this restroom

10:16.183 --> 10:18.652
has the paper
hanging over, not under,

10:18.719 --> 10:21.989
and they were installed
by professionals.

10:22.055 --> 10:23.156
Does it matter?

10:23.223 --> 10:25.158
(CELLPHONE BUZZES)

10:25.225 --> 10:28.028
I-D-G-A...

10:29.763 --> 10:32.199
I think it's an acronym

10:32.265 --> 10:34.768
or maybe even an anagram.

10:36.136 --> 10:40.207
I don't think Lea cares about
the toilet paper debate.

10:40.273 --> 10:42.810
It's not a debate.
I'm right.

10:42.876 --> 10:45.012
I think you should
talk to Lea.

10:45.078 --> 10:47.047
Not text, talk.

10:49.683 --> 10:51.719
Did you talk to Dr. Melendez

10:51.785 --> 10:53.687
after you got in trouble
with him?

10:53.754 --> 10:54.822
No.

10:54.888 --> 10:55.989
Why not?

10:56.056 --> 10:58.225
Because I did nothing wrong.

10:58.291 --> 11:00.694
Because you were right.

11:00.761 --> 11:02.595
Yeah.
So am I.

11:05.232 --> 11:06.566
(SIGHS)

11:06.633 --> 11:09.937
IRIS: Make sure all four tips
are touching the ground

11:10.003 --> 11:11.538
before you take a step.

11:11.604 --> 11:13.073
Well, thank you, Iris.

11:13.140 --> 11:14.574
I never would have
figured that out.

11:14.641 --> 11:17.911
I'm required to show you how
to use all medical equipment.

11:17.978 --> 11:19.312
(DOORBELL RINGS)

11:19.379 --> 11:21.715
Well, I'm not gonna use it.
You want to know why?
Huh?

11:21.782 --> 11:24.718
Because I'm not gonna use it.

11:24.785 --> 11:26.920
You remind me of
my Grandpa Eddie.

11:26.987 --> 11:28.655
So grumpy, so adorable.

11:28.722 --> 11:30.724
See? Look, no hands.

11:30.791 --> 11:32.159
I'm fine.

11:34.194 --> 11:37.030
Uh, chicken soup,
heard it's good for the soul.

11:37.097 --> 11:39.132
I wasn't expecting you.
Thank you.

11:39.199 --> 11:40.901
That's very thoughtful.

11:40.968 --> 11:43.136
It's... Really,
it's no big deal.

11:43.203 --> 11:45.873
I signed up to bring you food
at the hospital,

11:45.939 --> 11:47.474
the Meal Train
that they set up.

11:47.540 --> 11:49.476
The Meal Train, yeah.
Yeah.

11:51.311 --> 11:53.814
How... How are you
doing today?

11:53.881 --> 11:56.316
Well, today is
actually looking up.

11:56.383 --> 11:57.617
Good.

11:57.684 --> 11:58.986
You want to come in
and have some soup?

11:59.052 --> 12:02.155
I have other plans.

12:02.222 --> 12:03.290
Ah, yeah.

12:03.356 --> 12:04.792
But, um...

12:04.858 --> 12:06.726
I'm actually
free tomorrow.

12:07.427 --> 12:09.262
Do you like lasagna?

12:09.329 --> 12:10.931
I kind of love lasagna.

12:10.998 --> 12:12.332
Great.

12:12.399 --> 12:15.702
Finally get that second date.

12:15.769 --> 12:17.771
You know,
you don't have to...
No, Aaron.

12:17.838 --> 12:19.339
I want to.

12:19.406 --> 12:21.074
Well, then, I want to.

12:21.141 --> 12:22.475
(CHUCKLES)

12:22.542 --> 12:24.177
Okay. Great.

12:24.244 --> 12:25.813
Then, um...

12:25.879 --> 12:27.447
I will see you,
then, tomorrow.

12:27.514 --> 12:28.982
I'll see you tomorrow.

12:30.383 --> 12:32.019
(MONITOR BEEPING)

12:32.085 --> 12:35.188
No one dabbles in archery
unless they're at summer camp.

12:35.255 --> 12:36.423
How long did you do it?

12:36.489 --> 12:38.792
Seven days a week
for seven years.

12:38.859 --> 12:40.127
Why'd you stop?

12:40.193 --> 12:43.196
It was just time to go to
college, medical school,

12:43.263 --> 12:44.965
be a grown-up.

12:45.032 --> 12:46.533
It was that easy
to just quit?

12:46.599 --> 12:50.003
Archery doesn't fill concert
halls or pay the bills.

12:50.070 --> 12:53.206
She has a slight fever,

12:53.273 --> 12:56.443
her rash is spreading,
and she has edema.

12:56.509 --> 12:58.846
This is definitely
not paronychia.

12:58.912 --> 13:01.548
I know.
I've moved on to MRSA.

13:01.614 --> 13:05.185
That's possible,
but you should want proof.

13:05.252 --> 13:08.688
If we do an open,
deep-tissue biopsy,

13:08.755 --> 13:10.991
we will know for sure if
you have flesh-eating...

13:11.058 --> 13:12.592
Shaun.

13:12.659 --> 13:14.828
(BEEPING CONTINUES)

13:14.895 --> 13:17.564
(INDISTINCT PA ANNOUNCEMENT)

13:19.799 --> 13:21.401
Part of being
a good doctor
is knowing

13:21.468 --> 13:23.937
when to not scare the crap
out of a patient.

13:24.004 --> 13:26.173
I don't think so.

13:26.239 --> 13:28.141
This is your problem,
not hers,

13:28.208 --> 13:31.044
your need to be sure,
your obsession...

13:31.111 --> 13:34.047
We need to cut off
a small piece of her finger

13:34.114 --> 13:36.884
so we know if we have
to cut off a larger...

13:36.950 --> 13:39.853
Shaun, you're acting like
you want to amputate her hand.

13:39.920 --> 13:44.557
No. You're acting
like you don't
want to amputate her hand.

13:44.624 --> 13:46.193
I don't.

13:46.259 --> 13:49.596
But that's not
medically relevant.

13:50.330 --> 13:52.966
Her temperature is 102.

13:54.801 --> 13:57.938
It's gone up two degrees
since we've been arguing.

13:58.005 --> 14:00.007
**

14:05.245 --> 14:07.881
Okay. We'll test her.

14:13.286 --> 14:15.788
That tissue has begun to die.

14:17.024 --> 14:18.892
Or it's
inflammatory infiltration.

14:19.592 --> 14:21.128
Find anything?

14:21.194 --> 14:22.795
We're at an impasse.

14:22.862 --> 14:25.265
**

14:28.601 --> 14:31.138
Look here, at the margin.

14:31.204 --> 14:33.606
Subcutaneous fat
and fascial necrosis.

14:34.141 --> 14:35.475
Shaun was right.

14:36.743 --> 14:38.278
Let's go try to
save her hand.

14:38.345 --> 14:40.347
**

14:45.218 --> 14:47.220
**

14:51.058 --> 14:54.427
She is a young girl
with a lot going on.

14:54.494 --> 14:55.595
Well, we agree
on that much.

14:55.662 --> 14:57.264
That's why she needs
to see a shrink.

14:57.330 --> 14:59.666
Mmm. This...

15:01.168 --> 15:02.669
This feels different.

15:07.540 --> 15:09.642
What, you don't believe in
emotional intelligence?

15:09.709 --> 15:12.112
If I have to choose
between the battery
of tests we've done

15:12.179 --> 15:15.715
and your gut,
it's an easy choice.

15:15.782 --> 15:19.119
No. You don't relate to her,

15:19.186 --> 15:21.888
and if you don't
relate to her,
you can't understand her.

15:24.257 --> 15:25.725
You're probably right.

15:27.694 --> 15:29.262
You think you do relate.

15:30.663 --> 15:31.931
Well, do you have a kid?

15:35.068 --> 15:37.504
My opinion about Riley
is medical.

15:39.706 --> 15:43.210
Why haven't you
told any of us
you have a kid?

15:43.276 --> 15:45.878
That is a huge chunk
of your life
you've been hiding.

15:45.945 --> 15:47.614
I don't feel the need
to share everything

15:47.680 --> 15:50.383
about my personal life
with the people I work with.

15:50.450 --> 15:51.918
Oh, that's your
passive-aggressive way

15:51.985 --> 15:53.186
of saying
I'm an over-sharer?

15:53.253 --> 15:54.354
Yeah.

15:54.421 --> 15:56.823
Your opinion on Riley
is clearly skewed

15:56.889 --> 15:59.459
because you're looking at her
through a parental lens.

15:59.526 --> 16:01.028
I've been in her shoes.

16:01.094 --> 16:03.363
I'm better equipped
to evaluate her situation.

16:03.430 --> 16:05.498
You're the poster child
of skewed.

16:05.565 --> 16:06.866
You're too
emotionally involved

16:06.933 --> 16:08.835
and are overreacting
because you had a crappy mom

16:08.901 --> 16:10.337
who didn't care about you.
(LAUGHS)

16:10.403 --> 16:12.705
And why do I know all that?

16:12.772 --> 16:14.407
Because you're an over-sharer.

16:14.474 --> 16:16.409
(INHALES SHARPLY)
(MONITOR BEEPS)

16:18.911 --> 16:20.480
The scan's clean.

16:24.451 --> 16:26.019
Is it time to send her home?

16:28.455 --> 16:29.889
DR. MELENDEZ: Clamp.

16:30.623 --> 16:32.559
(MONITOR BEEPING)

16:32.625 --> 16:35.362
Whoa. That is not good.

16:35.428 --> 16:38.031
Muscle's weak. Clamp slid
right through the fascia.

16:38.098 --> 16:39.832
Murphy,
pull the skin back.

16:41.334 --> 16:43.303
SHAUN:
Smells like rotten eggs.

16:44.104 --> 16:45.705
There's only tissue damage.

16:45.772 --> 16:47.040
If we debride
her hand carefully,

16:47.107 --> 16:49.076
we can preserve
some mobility and dexterity.

16:49.142 --> 16:51.678
She's gonna need close
monitoring post-op tonight.

16:52.312 --> 16:53.780
Scissors.

16:55.582 --> 16:56.749
(LIGHT SWITCH CLICKS)

17:12.399 --> 17:13.866
(LIGHT SWITCH CLICKS)

17:18.838 --> 17:21.074
We need to talk.

17:21.141 --> 17:23.143
Can it wait? I'm late for
an all-night coding session.

17:23.210 --> 17:26.313
You hung the toilet paper
incorrectly.

17:26.379 --> 17:27.780
Right. Did you flip it?

17:29.316 --> 17:30.683
Great, we're done.

17:32.652 --> 17:35.755
You left the TV remote
on the couch.

17:35.822 --> 17:37.290
Shaun, I'm running late.

17:37.357 --> 17:41.161
You have to put it on the tray
on the coffee table.

17:41.228 --> 17:42.829
That is where it belongs.

17:42.895 --> 17:45.932
If it doesn't have
a set place,

17:45.998 --> 17:49.802
then it will be in many places
and then it will get lost

17:49.869 --> 17:52.672
and if I can't find it,
I can't watch
the Weather Channel...

17:52.739 --> 17:55.007
Okay, enough about
the damn remote!

17:55.074 --> 17:57.610
Everything in this place
has to be your way.

17:57.677 --> 18:00.046
We have to make sure
to use two pods
in the washing machine,

18:00.113 --> 18:01.948
we have to keep the cups
to the left of the plate,

18:02.014 --> 18:04.851
we have to keep
the air conditioner
at exactly 74,

18:04.917 --> 18:06.653
and we have to use
one very specific,

18:06.719 --> 18:08.188
very hard-to-find
toilet paper.

18:08.255 --> 18:09.822
And I'm trying
to be accommodating,

18:09.889 --> 18:11.858
but you are not
cutting me any slack.

18:11.924 --> 18:14.194
**

18:15.762 --> 18:16.996
Oh, God.

18:17.564 --> 18:19.199
Shaun.

18:19.266 --> 18:21.868
Shaun, I am sorry.
I'm... Are you okay?

18:22.369 --> 18:24.237
**

18:27.407 --> 18:29.309
**

18:32.745 --> 18:34.947
You have
a ruptured Achilles.

18:35.014 --> 18:36.549
I'm afraid your weekend
warrior days are over--

18:36.616 --> 18:37.850
Help! Can we get
some help here?

18:37.917 --> 18:39.786
Right there.

18:39.852 --> 18:40.953
CLAIRE: What happened?

18:41.020 --> 18:43.590
She couldn't sleep, uh,
she spiked a fever.

18:43.656 --> 18:44.991
It's only getting worse.

18:45.057 --> 18:46.693
(BREATHING RAGGEDLY)
I can't breathe.

18:46.759 --> 18:49.128
Take a deep breath,
in, out.

18:49.196 --> 18:51.198
(THERMOMETER BEEPS)
104.6.

18:51.264 --> 18:52.899
I need IV acetaminophen
and cooling blankets ASAP.

18:52.965 --> 18:54.967
She's tachypneic
with an O2 SAT of 87.

18:55.034 --> 18:56.703
Is this...
Is this something new or...

18:56.769 --> 18:57.970
Did... I mean, did she
do this to herself?

18:58.037 --> 18:59.038
She has an infection.

18:59.105 --> 19:00.507
I think she's
developed pneumonia

19:00.573 --> 19:02.074
due to an
underlying condition.

19:02.141 --> 19:03.210
What underlying condition?

19:03.276 --> 19:05.245
I have no idea.
Page Park and Lim.

19:09.249 --> 19:10.983
No signs of PE
or pneumonia.

19:11.050 --> 19:13.253
CFTR was negative
for cystic fibrosis.

19:13.320 --> 19:17.390
I think we may have missed
something on her CT.

19:17.457 --> 19:20.827
There...
that slight shadow
on the bronchus.

19:20.893 --> 19:22.562
A slow-growing
carcinoid tumor

19:22.629 --> 19:24.731
could cause chronic
airway inflammation.

19:24.797 --> 19:26.766
As the tumor grows,
symptoms worsen,

19:26.833 --> 19:29.436
leading to airway
obstruction and infection.

19:29.502 --> 19:31.371
Or it's just a shadow,

19:31.438 --> 19:32.839
a slight shadow.

19:32.905 --> 19:34.441
It is pretty subtle.

19:34.507 --> 19:37.043
I would like to do
exploratory VATS.

19:37.109 --> 19:39.078
You want to poke holes
in her chest

19:39.145 --> 19:40.880
and go rooting around
in her lungs?

19:40.947 --> 19:42.449
DR. PARK: Riley's body's
already compromised.

19:42.515 --> 19:44.116
There are no obvious lesions,

19:44.183 --> 19:45.718
and her symptoms
are more likely indicators

19:45.785 --> 19:47.186
of a simple sinus infection.

19:47.254 --> 19:49.722
The safer, better plan is
to treat with antibiotics.

19:49.789 --> 19:51.624
If she has
a progressing tumor,

19:51.691 --> 19:53.793
we can't just send her home
with medication.

19:59.532 --> 20:02.269
Pitch the surgery
to the parents and Riley.

20:02.335 --> 20:03.570
Okay.

20:09.942 --> 20:11.478
Hey, hey, hey!

20:11.544 --> 20:13.480
Don't touch those.
Those are vintage.

20:13.546 --> 20:15.147
Well, I'm just scooting
your toys over

20:15.214 --> 20:16.749
so it's easier to get
to your medication.

20:16.816 --> 20:18.885
Toys. Toys?

20:18.951 --> 20:20.753
These are not toys.

20:20.820 --> 20:22.322
That's Reggie Jackson.

20:22.389 --> 20:24.056
IRIS: Well, when
that timer goes off,

20:24.123 --> 20:25.758
Roger Johnson
can give you your medicine.

20:25.825 --> 20:27.460
Reggie Jackson.

20:27.527 --> 20:29.296
(DOORBELL RINGS)

20:30.129 --> 20:31.764
Hey, guess what.

20:33.533 --> 20:35.001
Quitting time.

20:35.868 --> 20:37.103
Okay. Have fun.

20:37.169 --> 20:39.772
Take your pills.
Yeah. (INHALES SHARPLY)

20:39.839 --> 20:40.973
(DOORBELL RINGS)

20:41.040 --> 20:42.141
(EXHALES HEAVILY)

20:45.412 --> 20:47.179
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

20:48.315 --> 20:49.982
I think I broke Shaun.

20:50.049 --> 20:52.151
Hi.
We got into
a big fight, huge,

20:52.218 --> 20:53.620
and I was yelling
and he just fell apart.

20:53.686 --> 20:55.154
It was awful.

20:55.221 --> 20:57.490
And he pushes and pushes
and pushes. I pushed back.

20:57.557 --> 20:59.459
Well, Shaun's not easy,
but you knew that.

20:59.526 --> 21:02.295
I knew it was gonna be hard,
but living with him is a lot.

21:02.362 --> 21:04.564
I know.
I mean, there's stuff
I've never even thought about.

21:04.631 --> 21:06.098
And I know he has
idiosyncrasies,

21:06.165 --> 21:08.335
but there's a lot of them.
I mean, a lot.

21:08.401 --> 21:09.836
I know.
Is Shaun okay?

21:09.902 --> 21:11.203
Yes. No. I don't know.

21:11.270 --> 21:13.205
He's at work.

21:13.272 --> 21:15.542
Glassy, you know him,

21:15.608 --> 21:17.377
like really know him.

21:18.411 --> 21:20.146
How do I deal with Shaun?

21:20.212 --> 21:23.149
Well, it's been 12 years,
and I'm still learning.

21:23.215 --> 21:24.717
He just always
has to be right.

21:24.784 --> 21:26.853
I mean, do you...
do you know how many
calls and texts

21:26.919 --> 21:29.889
and notes he's left me about
how I'm doing stuff wrong?

21:29.956 --> 21:31.157
I have a pretty good idea,
yeah.

21:31.223 --> 21:33.125
Yeah, well,
it's exhausting.

21:33.192 --> 21:34.761
You know what?
We all have quirks.

21:34.827 --> 21:38.197
We can all be
a pain in the ass
from time to time.

21:38.264 --> 21:40.467
Okay, admittedly
Shaun a little more so.

21:40.533 --> 21:42.669
That is not helpful.

21:42.735 --> 21:44.070
Sit down.
What?

21:44.136 --> 21:45.304
Sit down.
Why?

21:45.372 --> 21:47.907
Why? Because you're agitated
and you're annoying me

21:47.974 --> 21:50.242
and I can't give you
good advice in that state.

21:51.478 --> 21:52.645
Sit.

21:57.283 --> 21:58.317
Thank you.

22:00.920 --> 22:02.755
Do you like Shaun?

22:02.822 --> 22:04.391
Of course.
Why?

22:06.292 --> 22:11.163
He's sweet, kind, honest,
sometimes brutally honest,

22:11.230 --> 22:14.701
there's never
an agenda with him.

22:14.767 --> 22:16.168
He's just Shaun.

22:17.437 --> 22:19.071
So?

22:19.138 --> 22:21.374
So I want him to change,

22:21.441 --> 22:23.242
a little.

22:23.309 --> 22:26.546
You moved in
expecting him to change?

22:26.613 --> 22:28.047
He doesn't want you
to change.

22:28.114 --> 22:29.281
I know that.

22:32.284 --> 22:36.122
And if I made
the wrong decision?

22:36.188 --> 22:39.592
Then you move out
and you do it right now.

22:39.659 --> 22:41.394
It'll devastate him,
but the longer you wait,

22:41.461 --> 22:44.196
the more... (SIGHS)

22:44.263 --> 22:46.065
...the worse
it will be for him.

22:52.672 --> 22:54.741
CLAIRE: If Riley has a tumor,

22:54.807 --> 22:58.578
we need to open her up
to find out what
we're dealing with.

22:58.645 --> 23:00.680
Why do you think
she has a tumor?

23:00.747 --> 23:03.215
It's consistent
with her symptoms.

23:03.282 --> 23:05.885
The same symptoms
she's been having
for years?

23:06.853 --> 23:08.588
Yes.

23:08.655 --> 23:11.658
The same symptoms we've been
told are psychological,

23:11.724 --> 23:14.827
the same symptoms
a dozen doctors have run

23:14.894 --> 23:17.263
a hundred tests for
and found nothing?

23:17.329 --> 23:20.066
There is a shadow
on her CT image.

23:20.667 --> 23:22.068
A shadow?

23:22.935 --> 23:24.537
And it's risky surgery?

23:26.873 --> 23:30.009
Opening her up
in a weakened state
could be dangerous.

23:32.111 --> 23:34.581
Look, I know Riley
frustrates you,

23:34.647 --> 23:36.816
drives you crazy,

23:38.017 --> 23:39.586
but I also know
you love her.

23:41.588 --> 23:43.590
You have a chance
to show her that.

23:44.657 --> 23:47.193
So you want to do this
as a statement?

23:47.259 --> 23:49.962
(MONITOR BEEPING)

23:50.029 --> 23:52.832
We want you to believe
in your daughter,

23:54.133 --> 23:55.768
because that's what
a parent does.

23:56.903 --> 23:59.105
**

24:01.541 --> 24:02.975
When she was little

24:03.776 --> 24:05.712
and had a bad dream,

24:07.446 --> 24:10.783
she used to come into our room
and snuggle up under your arm,

24:12.118 --> 24:14.086
just like she's doing to me.

24:15.221 --> 24:16.756
You would stroke her face

24:17.924 --> 24:20.627
until she was
finally at peace
and fell asleep.

24:22.161 --> 24:23.630
(SNIFFLES)

24:23.696 --> 24:25.598
(VOICE BREAKING)
She's in so much pain,

24:27.166 --> 24:29.335
and I don't know
how to make it go away.

24:30.102 --> 24:31.771
**

24:33.906 --> 24:35.407
(SNIFFS)

24:36.909 --> 24:38.077
Riley?

24:39.111 --> 24:40.547
Hey, um...

24:42.448 --> 24:43.716
The doctors,

24:43.783 --> 24:46.919
t-they want to see what's
going on in your lungs.

24:49.556 --> 24:51.257
They think you might
have a tumor.

24:55.995 --> 24:57.797
And we want them
to operate.

25:00.600 --> 25:02.569
You think I have
a real tumor?

25:04.436 --> 25:07.473
It's scary, I know,
but...

25:08.307 --> 25:11.310
Yes, we do.

25:12.444 --> 25:14.614
**

25:16.983 --> 25:19.018
**

25:21.954 --> 25:23.590
(MONITOR BEEPING RAPIDLY)

25:23.656 --> 25:25.725
DR. REZNICK: Her BP's
dropping out... 73/51.

25:25.792 --> 25:28.928
Heart rate
is spiking to 137.

25:28.995 --> 25:31.363
Hang an IV saline bolus.
I need a 12-lead.

25:35.635 --> 25:37.469
The necrosis has migrated.

25:37.536 --> 25:38.771
She's septic.

25:38.838 --> 25:40.973
There's definite infiltration
to the bone.

25:41.040 --> 25:42.875
We're gonna have to
amputate her arm.

25:47.880 --> 25:49.649
(SAW BUZZING)

25:51.183 --> 25:52.985
(MONITOR BEEPING)

25:56.055 --> 25:57.624
DR. MELENDEZ: Polish the bone
to help stump healing.

25:58.390 --> 25:59.659
Rasp.

26:01.260 --> 26:04.030
SHAUN: The margins
appear to be clean.

26:06.032 --> 26:07.266
There's still
a small chance microbes

26:07.333 --> 26:08.635
may have spread
to her organs.

26:08.701 --> 26:10.169
If they did,
then her mortality rate

26:10.236 --> 26:11.671
just increased exponentially.

26:13.906 --> 26:16.643
What if we put her in
hyperbaric oxygen
therapy now?

26:16.709 --> 26:19.011
Oxygen's toxic
to bacteria.

26:19.078 --> 26:21.614
There's a lot of things
that could go wrong in there.

26:21.681 --> 26:22.782
We wouldn't be able to
decompress the chamber

26:22.849 --> 26:23.983
in time to help her.

26:26.218 --> 26:28.821
We wouldn't have to
wait to help her

26:28.888 --> 26:30.857
if someone goes in with her.

26:32.424 --> 26:33.793
I'll do it.

26:33.860 --> 26:35.628
Okay.
Get the chamber ready.

26:36.262 --> 26:38.397
**

26:40.432 --> 26:42.234
DR. LIM: Lung tissue
looks normal.

26:42.301 --> 26:44.170
DR. PARK: And there are
healthy-appearing bronchi.

26:44.236 --> 26:45.705
Nothing,

26:45.772 --> 26:47.039
yet.

26:49.308 --> 26:50.710
(MONITOR BEEPING RAPIDLY)

26:50.777 --> 26:52.144
DR. LIM: Damn it.
Tore a lobar artery.

26:52.211 --> 26:55.214
JL: BP is 81/49,
oxygen SATS 93,

26:55.281 --> 26:57.383
heart rate is going up.
She is tanking.

26:57.449 --> 26:59.852
DR. LIM: Park,
I need more suction.
I can't see a thing in here.

26:59.919 --> 27:01.487
We need to do
an open thoracotomy now.

27:01.553 --> 27:03.923
Browne, crack her chest.
10 blade and a rib spreader.

27:09.862 --> 27:14.033
There are only
7.18 cubic meters in there.

27:15.201 --> 27:16.335
How does it feel?

27:17.336 --> 27:18.905
It's fine.

27:18.971 --> 27:21.340
I thought it might feel
claustrophobic

27:21.407 --> 27:22.942
for someone neurotypical.

27:24.210 --> 27:25.444
It is.

27:27.479 --> 27:29.648
(MONITOR BEEPING RAPIDLY)

27:30.917 --> 27:32.151
CLAIRE: Got it.

27:32.218 --> 27:34.253
It's still bleeding.

27:34.320 --> 27:36.155
JL: Stroke volume
just bottomed out.

27:36.222 --> 27:38.257
CLAIRE: Rapid infuse
four liters of whole blood.

27:38.324 --> 27:40.292
DR. LIM: Get ready to start
cardiac massage.

27:40.359 --> 27:42.695
Wait. I think I have
an anchor
in the arterial wall.

27:43.796 --> 27:46.265
JL: Stroke volume is rising,

27:46.332 --> 27:50.002
BP increasing, 90/60.

27:50.069 --> 27:51.704
Pulse is 90 and regular.

27:51.771 --> 27:53.305
She's stable for now.

27:54.473 --> 27:55.808
(MONITOR BEEPING STEADILY)

27:59.779 --> 28:01.247
This was a mistake.

28:01.313 --> 28:03.649
We need to close her up
as soon as possible.

28:07.787 --> 28:09.688
DR. LIM:
It doesn't make any sense.

28:11.323 --> 28:13.259
Her arterial wall
shouldn't be this fragile.

28:14.293 --> 28:16.328
Something else has caused it
to thin out.

28:18.798 --> 28:20.967
What else is going on
in here?

28:21.033 --> 28:22.634
Browne, I need more light.

28:23.135 --> 28:25.404
**

28:27.106 --> 28:28.741
Yeah. See that?

28:30.276 --> 28:33.112
A localized granuloma
on the right lower lobe.

28:33.179 --> 28:34.346
You think it's cancer?

28:34.413 --> 28:35.948
DR. LIM: Not sure,
but something's in there.

28:36.015 --> 28:37.884
Park, retract the lung.

28:37.950 --> 28:39.685
(BEEPING CONTINUES)

28:40.719 --> 28:43.155
**

28:51.430 --> 28:53.099
It's a LEGO.

28:53.165 --> 28:54.834
Riley must've inhaled it
years ago.

28:54.901 --> 28:56.368
CLAIRE:
It settled in your lung

28:56.435 --> 28:59.171
and became encased
in inflammatory tissue.

28:59.238 --> 29:02.074
Your body's immune response
attacked it,

29:02.141 --> 29:04.977
making you progressively
more sick over the years.

29:05.044 --> 29:07.513
DR. PARK: It's small, thin,
and made of plastic.

29:07.579 --> 29:09.782
There was no way of seeing it
on any of the imaging.

29:09.849 --> 29:11.550
Ugh. This is so gross.

29:13.219 --> 29:14.987
I'm gonna make it
into a necklace.

29:15.054 --> 29:16.422
(LAUGHTER)

29:17.890 --> 29:19.258
Good luck.
Excuse me.

29:25.264 --> 29:27.800
We're sorry that
we didn't believe in you.

29:31.337 --> 29:33.973
We're sorry that we put
you through all this.

29:38.177 --> 29:40.012
We're sorry
that we got divorced.

29:40.079 --> 29:41.447
Whoa.

29:41.513 --> 29:44.050
You guys are
way better off apart.

29:44.116 --> 29:47.286
We always thought you were
upset because we split up.

29:47.353 --> 29:50.456
I was upset because
you fought all the time.

29:50.522 --> 29:52.124
You still do.

29:52.191 --> 29:53.425
It freaked me out.

29:55.627 --> 29:57.897
So I'd hide
in my princess tent,

29:57.964 --> 30:01.200
bite my nails,
gnaw on crayons...

30:03.235 --> 30:06.172
...chew on LEGOs.
(CHUCKLES)

30:06.238 --> 30:07.739
We screwed up,

30:09.208 --> 30:11.643
and we promise
we can do better.

30:13.145 --> 30:15.781
**

30:25.391 --> 30:27.559
I am not saying
that Ordinary People

30:27.626 --> 30:29.195
is not a good movie.

30:29.261 --> 30:30.796
It's a good...
It's a great movie.

30:30.863 --> 30:32.398
(CHUCKLES)
It's a great movie.

30:32.464 --> 30:34.033
Okay, but I'm saying
is that Raging Bull

30:34.100 --> 30:36.502
is a superior
cinematic experience.

30:36.568 --> 30:39.238
It is raw.
It's, like, romantic.

30:39.305 --> 30:41.207
It's romantic?
Yeah!

30:41.273 --> 30:42.508
It pummels you
from start to finish.

30:42.574 --> 30:44.210
Exactly. Exactly.

30:44.276 --> 30:46.645
It's like adrenaline is
pulsing through your veins.

30:46.712 --> 30:49.181
It leaves me breathless
every time I watch it.

30:50.016 --> 30:51.183
Oh!

30:52.018 --> 30:54.286
(SOFT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING)

30:55.787 --> 30:59.525
Do you... Do you want to,
like, go for a walk?

30:59.591 --> 31:01.293
Well, it's a little
cold outside.

31:01.994 --> 31:03.896
(BOTH LAUGH)

31:05.031 --> 31:06.732
I'm gonna kiss you.
You are?

31:06.798 --> 31:08.267
Uh-huh.
Okay.

31:09.801 --> 31:11.137
Mmm.

31:13.705 --> 31:14.806
Mmm.

31:14.873 --> 31:16.976
Maybe we'll walk upstairs?
Okay.

31:17.043 --> 31:18.310
Yeah?
Yeah.

31:18.377 --> 31:20.046
This way?
Yeah.

31:20.612 --> 31:22.548
Yeah.

31:22.614 --> 31:24.984
Whoa. (GROANS)

31:25.051 --> 31:26.953
(STUTTERS) Can I help?
No. Thank you.

31:27.019 --> 31:28.854
I'll get there.
I'm okay, I'm okay.

31:28.921 --> 31:30.289
I'm okay. Ow.

31:30.356 --> 31:32.258
(INHALES, EXHALES SHARPLY)

31:32.324 --> 31:34.860
**

31:37.896 --> 31:39.765
(MONITOR BEEPING)

31:50.876 --> 31:52.644
Is my hand okay?

31:55.114 --> 31:59.518
Your biopsy was positive
for necrotizing fasciitis.

31:59.585 --> 32:02.488
We had to do
multiple surgeries

32:02.554 --> 32:05.057
to remove the infected
muscle and bone.

32:05.691 --> 32:07.026
Bone?

32:08.961 --> 32:10.462
I'm so sorry, Jas.

32:10.529 --> 32:12.564
We had to amputate your arm.

32:13.832 --> 32:15.467
No.

32:15.534 --> 32:17.636
No, my...
my arm still hurts.

32:17.703 --> 32:20.106
I can... I can feel it.
It's still there.

32:22.874 --> 32:25.111
What you're experiencing
is "phantom pain."

32:26.145 --> 32:28.314
Your arm is gone.

32:28.380 --> 32:31.317
**

32:36.888 --> 32:38.157
(SOBS)

32:40.726 --> 32:41.927
H-He told you.

32:46.232 --> 32:47.599
My arm.

32:50.469 --> 32:52.404
(CRYING) My arm is gone.

32:56.608 --> 32:58.077
It's gone

32:58.144 --> 33:01.113
and it's...
it's your fault.

33:01.180 --> 33:02.881
(SNIFFLES)

33:03.982 --> 33:06.918
**

33:12.958 --> 33:14.593
(WEAKLY) Get out.

33:17.563 --> 33:19.131
Get the hell out.

33:20.566 --> 33:22.134
I can't.

33:23.335 --> 33:24.703
Neither of us can.

33:24.770 --> 33:25.837
(SNIFFLES)

33:28.607 --> 33:30.842
(SOBBING)

33:30.909 --> 33:33.679
**

33:35.281 --> 33:38.384
**

33:49.228 --> 33:50.862
You called it.

33:50.929 --> 33:52.164
Well done.

33:52.231 --> 33:53.932
Thanks for your help.

33:53.999 --> 33:57.736
Finally a believer
in the power
of emotional intelligence?

33:57.803 --> 33:59.605
Oh, it did get
her parents on board,

33:59.671 --> 34:01.540
even if it's only
for a little while.

34:01.607 --> 34:03.309
They believe their kid,

34:03.375 --> 34:05.544
and they're working on
their family relationships.

34:05.611 --> 34:07.012
It's pretty big steps.

34:07.079 --> 34:09.148
It was a nice moment.

34:09.215 --> 34:11.317
But if you think
you changed them,
that they'll be

34:11.383 --> 34:14.586
different people tomorrow
than they were yesterday,

34:14.653 --> 34:16.222
then you're kidding yourself.

34:19.825 --> 34:22.194
Right now, my emotional
intelligence is telling me

34:22.261 --> 34:23.862
even you don't believe that.

34:25.797 --> 34:27.199
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

34:27.266 --> 34:29.067
(ELEVATOR DOORS OPEN)

34:29.968 --> 34:32.871
**

34:36.375 --> 34:38.377
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

34:38.444 --> 34:40.212
Kitchen's clean,

34:41.413 --> 34:42.981
leftovers are in the fridge.

34:44.916 --> 34:46.385
How you doing?

34:47.519 --> 34:49.355
Fine.

34:49.421 --> 34:52.358
I just got
a little lightheaded.

34:52.424 --> 34:55.261
Balance isn't quite
back to normal.

34:56.862 --> 34:58.397
Well, now that you're
feeling a little better,

34:58.464 --> 34:59.898
you want to watch
Raging Bull?

35:02.033 --> 35:03.669
No.

35:03.735 --> 35:05.471
Okay. Another time.

35:06.438 --> 35:07.773
No.

35:09.275 --> 35:10.809
I can't do this.

35:10.876 --> 35:12.878
We can take it slow.

35:12.944 --> 35:16.648
I'm... I'm happy to just
be here with you, like this.

35:16.715 --> 35:19.551
No. I can't...
I can't be here like this.

35:22.888 --> 35:24.890
I-I don't want you to f...

35:26.124 --> 35:29.261
I just...
I don't want to...

35:31.930 --> 35:35.434
I'm sorry. I just...
I need you to go, please.

35:45.644 --> 35:48.447
**

35:51.483 --> 35:54.753
(DOOR OPENS, CLOSES)

35:54.820 --> 35:58.056
**

36:12.538 --> 36:16.107
**

36:21.680 --> 36:24.850
**

36:30.622 --> 36:34.660
Jas practiced violin
every day since
she was five.

36:37.796 --> 36:40.499
She put all her faith in me
to do the right thing, and...

36:42.734 --> 36:44.336
I thought I did. I...

36:47.939 --> 36:49.975
Shaun didn't care. He...

36:50.041 --> 36:53.412
He didn't see her dreams.
He just saw her symptoms.

36:57.148 --> 36:59.351
Sometimes that'll be
the wrong choice.

37:07.693 --> 37:11.763
My second year in the program,
there was this resident.

37:13.665 --> 37:15.166
She was kind of weird.

37:15.233 --> 37:17.002
She wore comic book T-shirts,

37:17.068 --> 37:19.571
always ate
the exact same lunch.

37:21.540 --> 37:24.810
But she was smart.

37:24.876 --> 37:27.513
She would get surgeries and
knock 'em out of the park

37:27.579 --> 37:29.315
over and over again.

37:30.482 --> 37:32.217
Couldn't stand her.

37:35.186 --> 37:39.325
And one day I realized
I was competing against her,

37:41.360 --> 37:43.729
but she wasn't competing
against me.

37:45.797 --> 37:48.867
She spent her time observing,
asking questions,

37:48.934 --> 37:52.771
preparing herself
to be a great surgeon.

37:55.974 --> 37:57.376
(SIGHS)

37:59.210 --> 38:00.546
Is she?

38:03.949 --> 38:07.085
Dr. Lim is one of
the best trauma surgeons
in the country.

38:16.662 --> 38:18.597
(SNIFFLES)

38:30.141 --> 38:31.477
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

38:35.681 --> 38:37.949
Dr. Melendez.
Dr. Browne.

38:39.150 --> 38:41.052
Dr. Lim.

38:41.119 --> 38:43.088
Nice save today.

38:43.154 --> 38:45.891
I heard.
Yes, good work, Dr. Browne.

38:45.957 --> 38:47.426
Thank you.

38:52.798 --> 38:54.265
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

38:54.332 --> 38:56.001
(ELEVATOR DOORS OPEN)

38:58.303 --> 38:59.638
Good night.

39:03.308 --> 39:05.577
(ELEVATOR DOORS CLOSE)

39:05.644 --> 39:08.213
You know she showed
bad judgment.

39:08.279 --> 39:10.281
You got something to say,
just say it.

39:13.184 --> 39:14.586
Want to grab a beer?

39:17.322 --> 39:18.690
Yes.

39:19.658 --> 39:21.527
(SIREN WAILS IN DISTANCE)

39:24.329 --> 39:25.664
Hey.

39:28.299 --> 39:29.835
Are you okay?

39:33.539 --> 39:34.840
Yes.

39:37.308 --> 39:40.812
I'm so sorry
for my outburst yesterday.

39:42.380 --> 39:44.349
I'm fine now.

39:47.519 --> 39:49.888
I'm not, Shaun.

39:51.289 --> 39:54.025
Coming back to California
and starting a new job

39:54.092 --> 39:55.961
and moving in with you...

39:56.027 --> 39:58.163
It's been so stressful,

39:58.229 --> 40:01.099
harder than I anticipated.

40:06.037 --> 40:07.839
You're moving out.

40:08.907 --> 40:11.009
No, I'm not moving out.

40:11.076 --> 40:14.446
We are still figuring out
each other's quirks.

40:14.513 --> 40:16.014
(EXHALES HEAVILY)
Oh, yes.

40:16.081 --> 40:18.484
You're very difficult
to live with.

40:18.550 --> 40:20.752
(LAUGHS)

40:20.819 --> 40:24.856
I know I forget stuff a lot,

40:24.923 --> 40:29.094
and sometimes I snap and yell.

40:29.928 --> 40:31.897
I promise to work on that.

40:33.532 --> 40:35.801
And I don't need you
to change,

40:35.867 --> 40:38.269
but I do need
to know that you know

40:39.137 --> 40:40.706
you're annoying as hell.

40:42.741 --> 40:46.912
I need to know that you'll
try to compromise.

40:54.986 --> 41:00.859
I don't think I can use
one-ply toilet paper.

41:00.926 --> 41:02.861
Oh, no, you were so right
about two-ply.

41:02.928 --> 41:05.697
Totally worth the extra $1.50.

41:05.764 --> 41:11.002
But maybe the cups can go
to the right of the plates.

41:13.138 --> 41:14.640
Sometimes.

41:18.343 --> 41:20.378
Well, everything's unpacked.

41:20.445 --> 41:23.882
We're officially
moved in together.

41:24.449 --> 41:26.885
(CHUCKLES)

41:26.952 --> 41:30.522
I'm gonna take these down
to the recycling.

41:30.589 --> 41:33.191
And I know I probably
didn't put everything
in the right place,

41:33.258 --> 41:36.327
but maybe we can
rearrange it together.

41:38.263 --> 41:41.099
I like that idea very much.

41:41.166 --> 41:43.535
(LEA CHUCKLES)

41:43.602 --> 41:45.136
(TONIGHT TONIGHT PLAYING)

41:45.203 --> 41:48.239
* All I am is all I need

41:48.306 --> 41:51.409
* And these city boy blues
and these suicide queens

41:51.476 --> 41:54.613
* And I said what I said
'cause I love you so much

41:54.680 --> 41:57.683
* Now I'm pulling these wires
on this cross-city bus

41:57.749 --> 42:01.052
* 'Cause tonight, tonight,
tonight, tonight

42:01.119 --> 42:04.322
* Yeah, tonight, tonight,
tonight, tonight

42:04.389 --> 42:07.458
* All I want
is what I can't take

42:07.525 --> 42:10.962
* But tonight, tonight,
tonight, tonight

42:11.029 --> 42:15.466
**

42:15.533 --> 42:18.303
I like that idea very much.

42:18.369 --> 42:19.638
* Tonight, tonight,
tonight, tonight *

42:21.206 --> 42:24.610
**

42:40.025 --> 42:44.095
**
